{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Laws passed by Parliament that are mandatory and legally binding.",
      "anchor": "The law of the land.",
      "misconception": "Believing that statutory regulations are just 'best practice' rather than criminal law."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Regulations",
      "simpleDefinition": "Industry-standard guides and codes of practice that provide advice on how to comply with the law.",
      "anchor": "Best practice guidance.",
      "misconception": "Thinking non-statutory documents have no legal weight; they are often used in court to prove a statutory duty was met."
    },
    {
      "term": "HASAWA (Health and Safety at Work Act)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The primary statutory legislation covering occupational health and safety in the UK.",
      "anchor": "The umbrella law.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it only applies to employers; it actually places duties on employees too."
    },
    {
      "term": "EAWR (Electricity at Work Regulations)",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory regulations specifically designed to prevent death or injury from electrical causes in the workplace.",
      "anchor": "The electrician's legal rulebook.",
      "misconception": "Confusing these legal requirements with the technical rules found in BS 7671."
    },
    {
      "term": "BS 7671",
      "simpleDefinition": "The UK national standard for electrical installations, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations.",
      "anchor": "The Big Blue Book.",
      "misconception": "Believing BS 7671 is a statutory law; it is actually a non-statutory document."
    },
    {
      "term": "ESQCR",
      "simpleDefinition": "Statutory regulations regarding the safety, quality, and continuity of the electricity supply.",
      "anchor": "The supplier's rules.",
      "misconception": "Thinking these apply only to internal house wiring; they primarily govern the supply and distribution network."
    },
    {
      "term": "On-Site Guide",
      "simpleDefinition": "A non-statutory publication that provides a simplified version of BS 7671 for small-scale installations.",
      "anchor": "The pocket guide.",
      "misconception": "Assuming the On-Site Guide replaces the full BS 7671 regulations."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means it is the law.",
    "Non-statutory means it is the industry standard.",
    "BS 7671 is non-statutory but essential for compliance.",
    "EAWR is a mandatory statutory requirement.",
    "Failure to follow statutory regulations is a criminal offense."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "BS 7671 is a law.",
    "Non-statutory documents can be safely ignored.",
    "HASAWA only applies to construction sites.",
    "All industry books carry the same legal weight."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Defining Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Define the term 'statutory' and its legal weight in the UK electrical industry.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the UK electrical industry, the term 'Statutory' means the document is a law passed by Parliament. You should think of these regulations as the 'law of the land.' Because they are legal requirements, compliance is mandatory for everyone—including employers, employees, and the self-employed.",
        "Failure to follow a statutory regulation is a criminal offense. This can lead to serious legal consequences, such as prosecution in a court of law, heavy fines, or even imprisonment. These are not suggestions or 'best practice' guides; they are strict legal obligations that carry the highest level of authority. You cannot choose to ignore a statutory regulation based on your professional opinion or a client's request. If a document is statutory, you must follow it to the letter to stay within the law."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether these documents are optional or if they are laws passed by Parliament."
    },
    {
      "title": "The Statutory Framework: HASAWA and EAWR",
      "objective": "Differentiate between the primary health and safety act and specific electrical regulations.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Statutory laws often work in a hierarchy. The Health and Safety at Work Act, abbreviated as HASAWA, is the primary 'umbrella' law for all workplaces. It sets out the general duties that employers have toward their employees and the public to ensure safety.",
        "Underneath this umbrella, we have more specific sets of rules called Regulations. For electricians, the most critical one is the Electricity at Work Regulations, or EAWR. While HASAWA covers safety in general (like keeping walkways clear), the EAWR focuses specifically on preventing death or injury from electrical causes, such as electric shock or burns. Both HASAWA and EAWR are statutory, meaning they are legally binding. If your work involves electricity, the EAWR is your primary legal rulebook, and you are legally required to comply with its safety standards."
      ],
      "hint": "Identify which document acts as the 'umbrella' law and which one focuses specifically on electrical safety."
    },
    {
      "title": "Identifying Specific Statutory Regulations",
      "objective": "Identify specific statutory regulations from the industry range.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Beyond HASAWA and EAWR, several other statutory regulations govern an electrician's daily work. The Electricity Safety, Quality and Continuity Regulations, known as ESQCR, primarily manage how electricity is supplied and distributed to properties by the network operators. For the tools and machinery we use, the Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations, or PUWER, ensures that equipment is safe and suitable for the task.",
        "Other essential laws include COSHH (Control of Substances Hazardous to Health) for handling chemicals, and CDM (Construction, Design and Management) for coordinating safety on construction sites. You must also follow the PPE (Personal Protective Equipment) at Work Regulations and the Manual Handling Operations Regulations. Every one of these is a statutory requirement, meaning they are mandatory laws that must be followed to prevent workplace accidents and legal prosecution."
      ],
      "hint": "Look for acronyms like ESQCR, PUWER, and COSHH which represent mandatory laws."
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-statutory Regulations and Guidance",
      "objective": "Define non-statutory regulations and identify BS 7671.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory documents are industry-standard guides and codes of practice. Unlike statutory laws, they are not passed by Parliament, so they are not 'the law of the land' in a direct sense. Instead, they represent 'best practice'—the agreed-upon professional way to do a job safely.",
        "The most famous example is BS 7671, also known as the IET Wiring Regulations or 'The Big Blue Book.' While BS 7671 itself is non-statutory, it is so highly respected that it is often used in court to prove that an electrician has met their statutory duties under the EAWR. Other examples include the On-Site Guide (a simplified version of BS 7671) and various Guidance Notes. Even though these are not laws, following them is the best way to ensure your work meets the required safety standards and is legally defensible."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that BS 7671 is the main industry standard, but it is not a law passed by Parliament."
    },
    {
      "title": "Categorizing Industry Documents",
      "objective": "Identify and categorize specific documents as statutory or non-statutory.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely and legally, you must be able to instantly categorize the documents you use. Statutory regulations are the mandatory laws: HASAWA (Health and Safety), EAWR (Electricity at Work), ESQCR (Supply and Distribution), and PUWER (Work Equipment). These are the rules you must follow to avoid criminal prosecution. They set the legal requirement for safety.",
        "On the other side, non-statutory guidance includes BS 7671 (The Wiring Regulations), the On-Site Guide, and various Codes of Practice. A common mistake is thinking BS 7671 is a law; it is actually a non-statutory standard. However, because it provides the technical detail needed to comply with the statutory EAWR, it is treated as the essential 'how-to' guide for the industry. Knowing the difference ensures you use the law for authority and the standards for technical execution."
      ],
      "hint": "Distinguish between the 'how-to' guides like BS 7671 and the 'must-do' laws like EAWR."
    }
  ]
}

